    <item>
      <title>Excercises</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/healthfitness/bullet-proofing/knee-pain/knees-over-toes/excercises/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2026 02:43:18 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/healthfitness/bullet-proofing/knee-pain/knees-over-toes/excercises/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://localhost:1313/knee-ability-zero/&#34;&gt;Knee Ability Zero&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Not in zero&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;reverse squats (the hip flexor loaded ones) - toes to bar if you can&amp;rsquo;t&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h4 id=&#34;non-knees-over-toes&#34;&gt;Non knees over toes&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Single leg squats&lt;br&gt;&#xA;5 minute squat&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h4 id=&#34;knees-over-toes&#34;&gt;Knees over toes&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Never work through pain during training&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;What frequency? - Talk to actual PT people too&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;a href=&#34;https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4nhuBzBjWzQ&#34;&gt;The 7 ATG Mobility Standards Checklist&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;In this one he gives a frequency&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;img src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/KC7pegk.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;All of the moves in the system ^assuming those are all the moves in the system regress too&lt;br&gt;&#xA;9:02 he talks about how the three programs&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Knee Ability Zero</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/healthfitness/bullet-proofing/knee-pain/knees-over-toes/knee-ability-zero/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2026 02:43:18 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/healthfitness/bullet-proofing/knee-pain/knees-over-toes/knee-ability-zero/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;[[#The Workout]]&lt;br&gt;&#xA;[[#Bonus]]&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h5 id=&#34;step-1-tibialis-raise&#34;&gt;Step 1: Tibialis Raise&lt;/h5&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/CA7IlhE.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;Further From the wall you get the easier it is&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h5 id=&#34;step-2-the-fhl-flexor-hallucis-longus-calf-raise&#34;&gt;STEP 2: THE FHL (FLEXOR HALLUCIS LONGUS) CALF RAISE&lt;/h5&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/shGCZKV.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;Farther from the wall the harder it is&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;img src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/m8gt07F.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://i.imgur.com/dsRRPLu.png&#34; alt=&#34;&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h5 id=&#34;step-4-the-patrick-step&#34;&gt;STEP 4: THE PATRICK STEP&lt;/h5&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I believe the Patrick Step is the most likely necessary accessory exercise to the ATG Split Squat, which can be used as a regression for beginners, and still as an effective warm-up for even the most advanced.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
